  "prompt": "What is the relation between frequency and time period?",
  "response": "The relationship between frequency and time period is **inverse**. Here\u2019s the detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Frequency (f)**: Frequency is the number of complete oscillations or cycles that occur in one second. It is measured in Hertz (Hz).\n\n2. **Time Period (T)**: The time period is the time taken to complete one full oscillation or cycle. It is measured in seconds (s).\n\n### Mathematical Relationship:\nThe frequency (\\( f \\)) and time period (\\( T \\)) are related by the formula:\n\n\\[\nf = \\frac{1}{T}\n\\]\n\nor equivalently:\n\n\\[\nT = \\frac{1}{f}\n\\]\n\n### Explanation:\n- If the frequency increases, the time period decreases, and vice versa.\n- For example, if the frequency is 50 Hz, the time period is \\( T = \\frac{1}{50} = 0.02 \\, \\text{s} \\).\n\n### Summary:\nFrequency and time period are inversely proportional: as one increases, the other decreases, and their product is always 1.",
